{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd3f06d2-ed87-4c2b-bafa-80c591e9aac6","content":"```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis uses the `dotnet test` filter to match any test whose fully qualified name contains `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds` while skipping the `EmailNotificationTests`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7fdb8785-b43c-47ac-9153-91448de5adc5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses its own test adapter and has its own filtering syntax. For TUnit, the filter to run a specific class uses the `--filter` option with `FullyQualifiedName` or `Class` filters.\n\nThe standard way to filter by class in `dotnet test` is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nor more precisely:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"Class~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nTUnit works with the standard dotnet test filtering since it integrates as a test framework. The filter syntax is the same as MSTest/xUnit/NUnit when using `dotnet test`.","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"67D2:228EC1:2CC7E8B:3160B79:69FD3DFD"},"id":"e06957a3-f76a-482d-9957-122776ca78a4","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:36:04.553Z","parentId":"1836f3a1-9e77-4d38-87f8-0fde18b49967"}
